data.content:
classification,type	LightRAG
RAG System
LightRAG is classified as a RAG system.

employs,uses	Gemini
LightRAG
LightRAG uses Gemini to answer.

condition,experience	Newborn
Physiological Neonatal Jaundice
Newborns commonly experience physiological neonatal jaundice.

diagnostic marker,prolonged duration	More Than 14 Days
Pathological Jaundice
Jaundice persisting beyond 14 days is a diagnostic marker suggesting the need to evaluate for pathological jaundice.

onset,timing	24 Hours
Physiological Neonatal Jaundice
Physiological neonatal jaundice typically appears after 24 hours.

association,symptom	Dangerous Signs
Pathological Jaundice
Pathological jaundice may be indicated by the presence of dangerous signs.

peak,progression	Days 3-5
Physiological Neonatal Jaundice
Physiological neonatal jaundice usually reaches its peak intensity between days 3-5.

includes,symptom	Dangerous Signs
Poor Feeding
Dangerous signs include poor feeding in newborns with jaundice.

diagnostic marker,early onset	24 Hours
Pathological Jaundice
Jaundice appearing before 24 hours is a diagnostic marker suggesting the need to evaluate for pathological jaundice.

duration,resolution	7-10 Days
Physiological Neonatal Jaundice
Physiological neonatal jaundice typically resolves after 7-10 days.

includes,symptom	Dangerous Signs
Fever
Dangerous signs include fever in newborns with jaundice.

includes,symptom	Dangerous Signs
Lethargy
Dangerous signs include lethargy in newborns with jaundice.

includes,symptom	Convulsions
Dangerous Signs
Dangerous signs include convulsions in newborns with jaundice.
